In [6]:
degree = nx.degree_centrality(G) # Add degree centrality
betweenness = nx.betweenness_centrality(G) # Add betweenness centrality
G_list = list(G.nodes())
G_dict = {}
for m,n in enumerate(G_list):
    G_dict[n]=n
# Run louvain community detection

# Add all attributes to graph
nx.set_node_attributes(G, degree, 'degree_centrality')
nx.set_node_attributes(G, betweenness, 'betweenness_centrality')
nx.set_node_attributes(G, G_dict, 'character')

Out[19]:

In my first static visualization, the nodes represent characters from Les Miserable, the musical. Each node is given a specific position, based on its betweenness centrality value. Using an algorithm that places nodes of more “storyline” importance closer to the center of the graph, I was able to represent a network of major and minor characters. Major characters are more central to the graph and minor characters more spread out around the edges of the graph. In addition to placement, each node is also color coded a different saturation of blue. The darker, more saturated nodes represent major characters; whereas the lighter, less saturated nodes denote minor characters. Also, each node’s size is also based on its degree centrality value. Major characters have larger nodes, but minor characters have smaller nodes. Finally, I labeled each node according to its character name, in order to help readers better understand the graph.

In my second dynamic visualization that I coded, I utilized the circular layout in order to help better position each node an equal distance from the center of the graph. It is more aesthetically pleasing to the viewer and easier to understand the data that it represents. Despite its stylish look, it does not order the nodes based on any kind of value. This is an unfortunate side effect of using the circular layout. However, because this is a dynamic visualization, it is interactive in that users can hover over the nodes and access its data. This data includes a character’s name, its betweenness centrality value and its degree centrality value. Once again betweenness centrality value signifies a node’s color (darker shades of blue for major characters and lighter shades of blue for minor characters) and degree centrality value determines the node’s size (larger nodes equal major characters and smaller nodes equal minor characters). Finally, this dynamic visualization has the ability to allow users to zoom in and out of the circular layout to find the smaller nodes and retrieve their data.
